WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.860 --> 00:00:13.560
&gt;&gt; Mary Jane Deeb: Good
afternoon, ladies and gentleman,

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:17.180
and welcome to the African
Middle/East Reading Room.

00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:19.520
I'm glad you're here.

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:26.000
This is the before last program
that we're going to be hosting

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.130
in this wonderful reading room.

00:00:29.130 --> 00:00:35.630
We are moving to the Northeast
Pavilion, which is behind me,

00:00:35.630 --> 00:00:39.670
over there, another very
beautiful reading room,

00:00:39.670 --> 00:00:46.190
in January and in the meantime,
we have to move out from here.

00:00:46.190 --> 00:00:50.260
So unfortunately, we will not
be hosting any more programs

00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:52.690
for the next three months.

00:00:52.690 --> 00:00:56.660
So you are here in a
way celebrating the last

00:00:56.660 --> 00:00:58.650
of what has been a very,

00:00:58.650 --> 00:01:02.220
very exciting time
in this reading room.

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:05.660
So we're all sad that we're
leaving but on the other hand,

00:01:05.660 --> 00:01:11.600
it's only temporarily stopping.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:16.630
We will resume our
exciting programs in January

00:01:16.630 --> 00:01:21.350
and we would invite you
then in a new environment

00:01:21.350 --> 00:01:23.910
but a very lovely one as well.

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:29.100
So I want to thank those
who have been coming

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:38.480
to these programs who have
been attending our series.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:44.790
I want to thank my own staff who
have been absolutely diligent

00:01:44.790 --> 00:01:51.810
until the last minute bringing
wonderful writers, thinkers,

00:01:51.810 --> 00:01:58.350
authors, scholars to this
reading room to share with us

00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:04.040
and with the public
outside around the nation,

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:07.810
around the world, the
scholarship and the thinking

00:02:07.810 --> 00:02:12.100
that has come through
their work, that has come

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:15.240
through these collections
that they have used.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:17.800
So it's only an au revoir.

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:24.950
It's not a goodbye but
it's just a short stop

00:02:24.950 --> 00:02:29.910
until we resume again
in January.

00:02:29.910 --> 00:02:34.350
So today we are very
fortunate to have

00:02:34.350 --> 00:02:43.040
with us Mr. Dawit Gebremichael
Habte who is going to be talking

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:48.360
about his own book, his
own story, his own past

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:53.560
and hopefully project into
the future a returning scholar

00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:56.530
to our reading room.

00:02:56.530 --> 00:03:00.390
We have not had many
programs on Eritrea

00:03:00.390 --> 00:03:05.940
and so it's very exciting to
have one today and to share

00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:13.700
with our patrons, with our
members here at the Library

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:19.180
and with the rest of the world
a story which is very exciting,

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:24.870
very moving and a story that
is shared by most people

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:28.570
around the country since
we're all at one time

00:03:28.570 --> 00:03:31.320
or another immigrants.

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:39.470
So to introduce the author, we
have our own Fentahun Tiruneh

00:03:39.470 --> 00:03:44.670
who has been forever
our Ethiopian

00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:48.330
and Eritrean specialist here
at the Library of Congress

00:03:48.330 --> 00:03:52.120
and who has done a fantastic
job building the collections.

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:56.780
So with no further ado, Fentahun
will introduce our speaker.

00:03:56.780 --> 00:03:59.080
Thank you.

00:04:01.470 --> 00:04:04.660
&gt;&gt; Fentahun Tiruneh:
Thank you, Mary Jane.

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:09.930
Ladies and gentleman, I
welcome you to today's program.

00:04:09.930 --> 00:04:13.480
My name is Fentahun Tiruneh
and I'm the area specialist

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:19.270
for the Ethiopian and
Eritrean collections.

00:04:19.270 --> 00:04:22.350
Today I present to
you a professional man

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:27.200
with unique story of
his immigrant life.

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:30.860
Raised in a tiny village
just south of Asmara,

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:36.250
the capital of Eritrea, Dawit
Gebremichael Habte fled to Kenya

00:04:36.250 --> 00:04:41.240
as a teenager and sought
asylum in the United States.

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:46.480
Dawit is now a father,
husband, software engineer,

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:52.080
and author of "Gratitude
in Low Voices: A Memoir."

00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:54.970
This story is a record
of a saga of a young man

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:57.490
who faced several
turbulent events

00:04:57.490 --> 00:05:00.160
in his immigrant life outside
of his family and country.

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:06.180
This story is told by
a very successful man

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:09.780
who withstood the
vagaries of immigrant life

00:05:09.780 --> 00:05:12.160
in different countries
and who finally made it

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:16.730
to the United States
to build a family life.

00:05:16.730 --> 00:05:20.210
His story encapsulates
the story of many of us

00:05:20.210 --> 00:05:24.220
from the same region but the
difference is Dawit took his

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:30.470
time and successfully published
his adventures into a book.

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:33.290
Instead of trying to
detail his life story,

00:05:33.290 --> 00:05:38.000
I'll let Dawit narrate
the rest of his adventure,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.270
country by country
and event by event.

00:05:42.270 --> 00:05:46.460
Dawit is featured in the
United States "USA Today,

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:48.570
New York Times, Associated
Press,

00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:52.540
and Johns Hopkins
Gazette' and has written

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:56.390
for various Eritrean
websites and publications.

00:05:56.390 --> 00:06:01.870
He lives in Maryland with
his wife and five children

00:06:01.870 --> 00:06:05.860
and works for Bloomberg BNA.

00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:09.740
Before I call on our
guest to the forum,

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:13.310
I'd like to make a
couple of announcements.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:17.540
This event is being videotaped
for subsequent broadcast

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:19.940
