00:41:21.350 --> 00:41:26.240
How do you go back and
remember names the way you did

00:41:26.240 --> 00:41:28.270
in the book [inaudible]?

00:41:28.270 --> 00:41:33.860
But for you, how do you
remember [inaudible]?

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:36.930
&gt;&gt; Dawit Gebremichael
Habte: Thank you.

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:41.360
Sophie [assumed spelling]
is asking me how the book is

00:41:41.360 --> 00:41:45.800
so detailed, how did you
remember the details in terms

00:41:45.800 --> 00:41:49.390
of places, names, and events?

00:41:49.390 --> 00:41:51.050
Were you taking notes?

00:41:51.050 --> 00:41:56.110
Do you have some kind of diary?

00:41:56.110 --> 00:41:57.830
I did take notes.

00:41:57.830 --> 00:42:01.210
The day that I left
home for some reason --

00:42:01.210 --> 00:42:04.330
We have this calendar it's
called [foreign word].

00:42:04.330 --> 00:42:07.140
It's a small calendar.

00:42:07.140 --> 00:42:09.500
I left home with that calendar.

00:42:09.500 --> 00:42:16.540
So starting from the 5:00 a.m.
we went to the airport to fly

00:42:16.540 --> 00:42:19.060
to [inaudible] and we didn't
catch the morning flight.

00:42:19.060 --> 00:42:22.480
So we had to take the
evening, the 6:00 pm flight.

00:42:22.480 --> 00:42:27.130
Starting from that, going
through the southern part

00:42:27.130 --> 00:42:31.200
of Ethiopia, the
forest and Kenya,

00:42:31.200 --> 00:42:35.410
through all that life I
was actually taking notes.

00:42:35.410 --> 00:42:41.490
That [foreign word] I still have
it and amazingly the benefit

00:42:41.490 --> 00:42:44.600
of that [foreign word]
was it completely took me

00:42:44.600 --> 00:42:49.310
out of my physical presence.

00:42:49.310 --> 00:42:54.530
Every time I went from my --
There were about seven of us.

00:42:54.530 --> 00:42:58.030
I went from the group
and started writing.

00:42:58.030 --> 00:43:00.450
I was going away from the --

00:43:00.450 --> 00:43:09.990
I basically I was transforming
mentally to a different place.

00:43:09.990 --> 00:43:16.280
So that made all the
suffering nonexistent.

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:23.690
And one of our colleagues
actually did tell me that,

00:43:23.690 --> 00:43:26.960
Dawit, why you even bother
to write this nonsense?

00:43:26.960 --> 00:43:29.150
Aren't we're going
to die anyway?

00:43:29.150 --> 00:43:30.900
Why bother?

00:43:30.900 --> 00:43:32.870
And my answer was
simply so what.

00:43:32.870 --> 00:43:37.400
I will be dying writing.

00:43:37.400 --> 00:43:42.640
So what's the point.

00:43:42.640 --> 00:43:47.870
In terms of remembering
my childhood,

00:43:47.870 --> 00:43:50.850
especially my childhood
activities

00:43:50.850 --> 00:43:55.030
and the treasure is I'm
extremely fortunate.

00:43:55.030 --> 00:43:57.560
I have people like
Daniel sitting right here.

00:43:57.560 --> 00:44:03.660
We got lost when we were
six or seven years old

00:44:03.660 --> 00:44:05.160
in the city of Asmara.

00:44:05.160 --> 00:44:08.570
So I have many of them and we
meet every day, every weekend,

00:44:08.570 --> 00:44:11.860
every month, every Saturday we
have a get together for Gejeret

00:44:11.860 --> 00:44:16.160
and what I did was after I wrote
it, I doubled checked with them

00:44:16.160 --> 00:44:20.510
and they gave me feedback
where yes, this is accurate.

00:44:20.510 --> 00:44:22.130
You may have missed this.

00:44:22.130 --> 00:44:28.640
That number you are wrong
because they give me names.

00:44:28.640 --> 00:44:32.290
So I was able to
get that information

00:44:32.290 --> 00:44:35.560
from my childhood friends.

00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:41.480
For the other personal stories
of the people, I actually went

00:44:41.480 --> 00:44:43.970
and interviewed all of them.

00:44:47.060 --> 00:44:57.980
Mebrahtu Negusse, [inaudible]
who was my angel who came

00:44:57.980 --> 00:45:01.820
from heaven to actually,
until six years old,

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:04.940
until six grader -- Until I was
in sixth grade, I didn't know

00:45:04.940 --> 00:45:08.400
to use dictionary and
until I met that guy,

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:10.530
his children showed me how
to use dictionary and how

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:13.880
to even they even showed
me what a library was.

00:45:13.880 --> 00:45:16.690
For him, I knew he
came to Boston.

00:45:16.690 --> 00:45:18.640
So I went, I drove there.

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:21.800
We spent three days
and nights interviewing

00:45:21.800 --> 00:45:25.220
and then getting all
the facts that I needed.

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:27.610
And after I wrote it,
I sent it back to him

00:45:27.610 --> 00:45:28.960
when we back to Eritrea.

00:45:28.960 --> 00:45:32.530
He reviewed so I did go back --
I did interview a lot of people

00:45:32.530 --> 00:45:39.300
because again, this is personal
story and it has to be accurate

00:45:39.300 --> 00:45:42.050
and it has to have
proper context.

