00:46:13.950 --> 00:46:15.250
&gt;&gt; Dawit Gebremichael
Habte: Yes.

00:46:15.250 --> 00:46:20.650
You are asking me to give
some context to the title

00:46:20.650 --> 00:46:26.950
and also describe to you why
"Gratitude in Low Voices."

00:46:26.950 --> 00:46:28.930
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I like the title.

00:46:28.930 --> 00:46:31.860
I like the title of the book.

00:46:31.860 --> 00:46:39.250
I'm not sure what
you meant by it.

00:46:39.250 --> 00:46:40.550
&gt;&gt; Dawit Gebremichael
Habte: Yes.

00:46:40.550 --> 00:46:41.900
Okay. It actually
came from the book

00:46:41.900 --> 00:46:47.560
and I am trying --
Yes, on page 36.

00:46:51.590 --> 00:46:56.600
Usually when I came home from
school with my test results,

00:46:56.600 --> 00:47:01.950
mom would say, "Son, how
did you do this time?"

00:47:01.950 --> 00:47:07.510
From her tone, I could easily
tell that she was concerned.

00:47:07.510 --> 00:47:11.660
Mom would start searching
from sticks marked with x

00:47:11.660 --> 00:47:14.960
in red pen on my exam papers.

00:47:14.960 --> 00:47:21.790
At times she would count two or
three x marks out of 20 or 30.

00:47:21.790 --> 00:47:24.950
Once she finished
counting the x marks,

00:47:24.950 --> 00:47:31.110
she would straighten her head
and say, "Son, what happened?

00:47:31.110 --> 00:47:33.940
Were you sleeping in class?"

00:47:33.940 --> 00:47:37.490
No, [foreign word],"
I would respond.

00:47:37.490 --> 00:47:39.010
[foreign word] is my mom.

00:47:39.010 --> 00:47:41.410
"Look, I got seven correct,"

00:47:41.410 --> 00:47:45.350
I would protest while
selectively placing my finger

00:47:45.350 --> 00:47:48.180
on the questions I
answered correctly.

00:47:48.180 --> 00:47:52.190
"Of course," mom would say,

00:47:52.190 --> 00:47:55.030
"why else would you
go to school then?

00:47:55.030 --> 00:47:57.340
I don't think you
understand my question.

00:47:57.340 --> 00:47:59.580
I'm asking you if
you were asleep

00:47:59.580 --> 00:48:01.320
in class half of the time.

00:48:01.320 --> 00:48:04.220
Otherwise, how could
you miss this many?

00:48:04.220 --> 00:48:09.870
But [foreign word], the others
got a lot more wrong than me.

00:48:09.870 --> 00:48:13.760
This is a good grade,"
I would protest.

00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:19.240
"Those are not kids,
son," my mom would say.

00:48:19.240 --> 00:48:23.100
Our exchange would continue
with my mom pulling me close

00:48:23.100 --> 00:48:26.020
to her for a warm hug.

00:48:26.020 --> 00:48:32.300
This time though, this is when
I brought an award from school.

00:48:32.300 --> 00:48:35.910
I was first from my first
grade so I brought an award.

00:48:35.910 --> 00:48:37.210
So this is the time.

00:48:37.210 --> 00:48:45.110
"This time though mom's tone was
more of excitement and elation.

00:48:45.110 --> 00:48:50.110
Grace be upon all you saints
for delivering my prayers

00:48:50.110 --> 00:48:52.490
to our father in heaven.

00:48:52.490 --> 00:48:56.400
Thank you, Saint Mary, for
watching over my family.

00:48:56.400 --> 00:49:00.490
Thank you, [inaudible],
for this day.

00:49:00.490 --> 00:49:04.680
The gratitude of my mother would
continue in low voices for me

00:49:04.680 --> 00:49:10.920
to hear until tears starting
wailing up in my mom's eyes.

00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:15.180
Mom then looked at me with
a big smile somewhat trying

00:49:15.180 --> 00:49:19.320
to hide her emotions.

00:49:19.320 --> 00:49:23.930
Mom's low voice and her broad
smile were the most powerful

00:49:23.930 --> 00:49:27.860
expressions of love and
compassion no amount

00:49:27.860 --> 00:49:30.600
of words could express.

00:49:31.830 --> 00:49:37.820
That's where the gratitude
in low voices came from.

00:49:37.820 --> 00:49:40.510
Thank you so much.

